							<td>

				<font SIZE="2">

							<p class="body"><i>During 1903 and 1904 The National 
							Builder published series of articles by the editor 
							of the magazine, Fred T. Hodgson, under the title 
							&quot;Some Builders' Tools - Their Use and Abuse&quot;.&nbsp; 
							The April, 1904 issue was dedicated in part to saws, with follow up articles in May and 
							June, 1904.</i></p>
							<p class="body"><i>I found this material a very 
							interesting read and worth of republishing here.&nbsp;
							<b>W.K.</b></i></p>
							<p>

							<img border="1" src="0_img/1904-S1.jpg"></p>
							<p class="body">
							<img border="1" src="0_img/Fred%20Thomas%20Hodgson-200.jpg" width="160" height="212" align="left" hspace="10" vspace="10">The tool next to the hammer that 
							claims the attention of the workman is the saw.</p>
							<p class="body">There are many varieties of this 
							tool, each kind being designed for some special 
							purpose, but the ordinary hand saw, as illustrated 
							in Fig. 3, is the one that will be called into use 
							the most. </p>
							<p class="body">When speaking of the &quot;hand saw&quot; it 
							must be understood that both the cross-cut and 
							rip-saw are meant, as they are somewhat alike, 
							except in the number of teeth, and the manner in 
							which they are filed. </p>
							<p align="center"><img border="1" src="0_img/1904-S0.jpg"></p>
							<p class="body">The teeth of the ordinary hand-saw 
							numbers about eight to the inch, while those of the 
							rip-saw do not number more than six to the inch, and 
							these are filed square across the face, or nearly 
							so, while the cross-cut or cut-off saw as it is 
							sometimes called, is filed up so as to show a fleam 
							tooth, that is, it has a cutting edge shown at each 
							tooth as represented at a Fig. 4, the cutting edge 
							showing alternately, as shown.</p>
							<p align="center"><img border="1" src="0_img/1904-S2.jpg"> </p>
							<p class="body">The teeth should be fully set and 
							well jointed, <i><b>a</b></i> shows the best tooth for soft wood; 
							<i><b>b</b></i> is better adapted for wood of medium hardness and 
							for mitering soft wood; <i><b>c</b></i> for harder wood, has the 
							back of the teeth filed square.&nbsp; For cutting timber, 
							the teeth are made much larger, but resemble those 
							in <i><b>b</b></i>, the set being increased with the wetness of 
							the wood. </p>
							<p class="body">The long cross-cut for two men is 
							toothed as at <b><i>i</i></b>, the cutting edge of the saw being 
							appreciably highest in the middle and gradually 
							tapering toward each end; the bevel shown is adapted 
							to soft or wet wood, and must be lessened for harder 
							or drier material; <i><b>k</b></i> represents a Yankee hook tooth, 
							which is based on the principle that while the fleam 
							teeth or knives cut into the wood, the hook teeth 
							remove the &quot;dust.&quot;&nbsp; These saws work easily and cut 
							rapidly. </p>
							<p class="body">The rake of a cross-cut saw is at 
							the side.&nbsp; It takes less inclination than the 
							cross-cut.&nbsp; The cross-cut requires finer and more 
							particular filing than the rip or web saw, and can 
							not be considered well filed unless a needle will 
							travel down the angular groove, which is formed by 
							the line of alternating points of teeth seen in all 
							well filed saws. </p>
							<p class="body">When the teeth are so regularly 
							formed that a needle will travel from end to end in 
							the angular groove, and the points are sharp and 
							keen, the saw will cut a kerf in the wood that will 
							have a flat bottom. The last teeth of cross-cuts may 
							be rounded at the points, to prevent tearing the 
							wood when entering the cut.</p>
							<p class="body">Back-saws are shown at <i><b>d </b>
							</i>and <b><i>e</i></b>, the 
							former suits soft wood, while the latter is for 
							harder woods and for mitering.&nbsp; The thinness of the 
							blade of the tenon or back saw is compensated for by 
							the metal back, which must be kept tightly in place 
							and straight.</p>
							<p class="body">The fleam tooth is illustrated at <i>
							<b>f</b></i>.&nbsp; It is adapted only for the softer kinds of wood; 
							which it cuts rapidly and smoothly.&nbsp; It has very 
							little set, and should be filed while laying down 
							quite flat.</p>
							<p class="body">Teeth for buck saws are shown at <b>
							<i>g</i></b> 
							and <b><i>h</i></b>, the former being for wet wood and the latter 
							for hard and dry.</p>
							<p class="body">Web, scroll and compass saws are 
							best provided with teeth as shown at <i><b>i</b></i>, for whilst 
							they have to perform both ripping and crosscutting, 
							a tooth adapted to the latter will perform the 
							former operation, though more slowly, but the 
							rip-saw will not do cross-cutting, so a tooth that 
							will in some measure do both is a necessity in saws 
							of the kind named.&nbsp; The backs of all saws of this 
							kind are ground thin so that little setting is 
							required.</p>
							<p class="body">The rip-saw for cutting wood 
							lengthwise requires an essentially different tooth 
							from the cross-cut.&nbsp; The teeth shown at <i><b>n</b></i> and 
							<b><i>m</i></b> are 
							of the proper shape, but they are not adapted for 
							hand saws, though all right for drill saws. The best 
							shape is that shown at <b><i>o</i></b>, though troublesome to file 
							it pays, because of its cutting so rapidly.</p>

				</font></td>
						</tr>
